580. res perinde sunt. ut agas, ‘everything depends on the way you do it, and the importance you attach to it.' Cf. Cic. de or. 111. 56. ²¹3 sed llaec omnia perinde sunt ut aguntur, ib. de off. 111. 33. 121, Stich. 520, Ter. Heaut. 195.

581. copias. This canticum is full of military metaphors, which are more frequent in the Pseudolus than in the other plays ; they were particularly suited for a Roman audience, and may be regarded as quite Plautus’ own.

583. maiorum, a seruus had no maiores, he was nullo patre. A stock joke in Latin comedy. Cf. Cas. 395, Pers. 391, Capt. 574 etc. Cf. infr. 590, where Pseudolus talks of his sellow-citizens (ciues), although according to Roman ideas no slave ever possessed the ciuitas.
